body: We currently show tests in the outline view if they match the pattern `group()` / `test()`. Flutter uses `testWidgets('name', () { }`, and other micro test frameworks layered on top of package:test have other patterns for the test name (`testUsingContext()`, ...). It would be nice to support these patterns as well.

comment_data.body: From some discussion, in order to be able to identify tests accurately, it would be good to have a `@isTest` or similar annotation - something that will tell us that `test()`, `testWidgets()`, `testWithContext()` ... are test definitions. The annotation would need to live somewhere general, and would be applied at the definition of the test method (not the use site - not on individual users tests).

Some background here:

- we currently show `package:test` tests in the Outline view in IntelliJ (powered by the analysis server's outline notification)
- this works by static analysis noting `test` method call sites, where the `test` symbol is traced back to something defined in `package:test/test.dart`
- this currently does not show Flutter's test methods (`testWidgets('foo', () { }`) or other micro frameworks on top of package:test (flutter_tools has one as well - `testWithContext()` - which is a wrapper around the regular `test` method)

I had a brief discussion with @scheglov about this - I was planning on adding support for test-like methods. This would have been done by id'ing method invocations with names like `testFooBar('test foo', ...)`. Konstantin had concerns that this would have false positives and be fragile.

One alternative approach would be to tag test method definitions with a common annotation. We could then know that uses of `test()`, `testWidgets()`, or `testWithContext()` if the definition of those methods were tagged with something like `@isTest` or `@definesTest`. If we choose to do that, we'd need to find a common place for the annotation to live. Good candidate places would be `package:meta`, or in `package:test` itself.

/cc'ing @grouma, @bwilkerson, @scheglov for thoughts
Having an annotation seems like a reasonable approach to me. I don't have strong feelings where the annotation lives. Maybe @natebosch or @jakemac53 have opinions?

I'd be in favor of having an annotation in `package:meta` and _using_ the annotation in `package:test`.  I like the idea of this being a general Dart concept with `package:test` being one particular usage.

On second thought, I think it makes more sense to reside in package:meta. I assume whatever tool is used to parse these annotations doesn't currently depend on package:test (in a non-dev context). Since package:test has tons of other dependencies it will be preferable to depend on package:meta only.

Pulling in many dependencies is a valid concern, but it seems to me that places that will use these new annotations (`@isTest` and `@isTestGroup`) already reference `package:test`. These are either helper methods in the `test` folder of a package, or in the `lib` folder of a specialized test package, like `package:flutter_test`. In any case, they already call `group()` or `test()`.

As for general concepts, it could be not the idea that there are alternative testing frameworks, but the idea that there are invocations of methods similar to `test()` that we want to show in the outline. But it is not `@isTest`, it is more like `@OutlineItem(kind, textArgumentIndex)` and `const isTest = const OutlineItem('test', 0)` is just one instance, declared in `package:test`. This way, if we get to the point when there is a need for general concept, we can generalize. But for now, I think `@isTest` and `isTestGroup` should live in `package:test`.

title: outline view should show tests for flutter code
